Consider the following code sample: 

```c#
#nullable enable
using System;
using System.Linq.Expressions;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

var collection = new Collection<Hamster>();
Hamster h = null!;
await collection.FooAsync(
    entity => entity.Name! == "bar",
    h);

public record Collection<T> 
    where T : Document
{
    public Task FooAsync<TDerived>(
        Expression<Func<TDerived, bool>> filter,
        TDerived td)
        where TDerived : T
    {
        throw new NotImplementedException();
    }

    public Task FooAsync<TDerived>(
        Task<TDerived> filterDefinition,
        TDerived td)
        where TDerived : T
    {
        throw new NotImplementedException();
    }
}

public sealed record HamsterCollection : Collection<Hamster>
{
}

public abstract class Document
{

}

public sealed class Hamster : Document
{
    public string? Name { get; private set; }
}
```

Compiling this code with .NET 5 SDK will succeed roughly 50% of the time. When the compilation fails the reported error is inability to infer the type of the following expression:

```c#
    entity => entity.Name! == "bar",
```

Now delete the `HamsterCollection` type in it's entirety and the compilation will succeed 100% of the time. It also succeeds if you change the declaration from `record` to `class`. There appears to be some race condition with records and inheritance here. 

This is a reduced sample from a bug report in [this tweet](https://twitter.com/i3arnon/status/1339631221052194820)

